<h1></h1>

I love breakfast. Either it's eggs or oatmeal, or superfood powered smoothie, I'll take it. For the last year I had developed this routine . Wake up at 6am. Glass of hot lemon water. Gym time. Shower. Breakfast around 8am - smoothie or oatmeal. And then work at 10am.

But two weeks ago I changed jobs and my routine got different. Some days I'm starting work at 7am. And I don't feel like waking up before 6am just to have time to make breakfast. I choose sleep. Therefore I looked in to some alternatives and gave a try to overnight oats. I tried them before a few times and liked them. But I never appreciated what a life saver they really are! It takes less than 5min to prepare them the night before. In the morning you just need to open the fridge, put the jar in your bag and you are good to go. You can eat them on the bus, metro or at your workplace. Brilliant! And they taste great, and you get all your nutritions to start a day. And we like nutritions, right?
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong> So here it is, my Life Saver Breakfast!</strong></p>
<a href="http://www.incurablyhappy.com/chef/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/20140307-133438-e1394197794815.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-60 alignleft aligncenter" alt="20140307-133438.jpg" src="http://www.incurablyhappy.com/chef/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/20140307-133438-e1394197794815-300x225.jpg" width="300" height="225" /></a>

&nbsp;

1 banana
2/3 cups of oats
1Tbsp chia seeds
1Tbsp goji berries
2Tbsp dried mulberries
1 cup your choice of milk (I use oat milk)
1 glass jar. Mine is 0.5 liter.

&nbsp;

<em>Instructions:</em> <span style="line-height: 1.5em;">On the bottom of the jar put 1/3 sliced banana. Top it with 1/3 of oats, chia, goji and mulberries. Cover everything with 1/3 of milk. And repeat this two more times.</span>

<img class="size-medium wp-image-68 alignright" alt="photo-4" src="http://www.incurablyhappy.com/chef/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/photo-4-300x220.jpg" width="300" height="220" />

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

The stuff in the jar should be liquid. That's how mine looked like:

<a href="http://www.incurablyhappy.com/chef/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/20140307-134340.jpg"><img class="size-full alignleft" alt="20140307-134340.jpg" src="http://www.incurablyhappy.com/chef/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/20140307-134340.jpg" width="2448" height="3264" /></a>
Now cover the jar and put it in the fridge overnight. In the morning just put the jar in your bag and you are good to go. No more excuses 'I have no time for breakfast'. It literally takes less than 5min to make it. You don't need to measure when you make it. Just add layers of oats, chia, whatever berries or fruit you want and enough liquid to cover everything. Give it a try!

Today I was thinking about my life in Norway, about friends, family and what does it mean to live in a foreign country. I moved to Norway more than four years ago. I believe that it was meant to be. My sister got a job offer in Oslo and I had an opportunity to come and finish my master studies at BI. It was easy to decide since my sister was going to move to the same city at the same time. I really wanted to study abroad and the timing seamed perfect. In the last four years happened a lot. I graduated, found my love, made new friends and finally figured out what I want to do in my life. I'm not sure how my life would have been if I stayed in Lithuania. But I am happy now and that is all what matters to me.

<a href="http://www.incurablyhappy.com/chef/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/meandzuzu.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-187" alt="meandzuzu" src="http://www.incurablyhappy.com/chef/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/meandzuzu-300x200.jpg" width="300" height="200" /></a>Living abroad is not easy. The beginning was tough. Suddenly you are in the new place where you don't know anything, you don't know the culture, people, places, language. You have to invest your time and energy in learning, meeting new people and making new friends outside your comfort zone. The most difficult for me was to be far away from my very good friends, whom I new since my childhood. Suddenly I had to make new friends. I am always glad to meet new people from different cultures and countries. But I don't believe you can become friends over night. For me it takes time to open up and let people in to my heart. I believe in quality and not quantity of friends. Even if I miss me Lithuanian friends and think about them quite often, after four years in Norway I can say that I have met people here whom I call friends and believe that our connection will last forever. I feel like I belong here and I call Oslo my home now.

The best thing about living in an international city as Oslo, is that you get to meet people from all over the world, you get to know their culture, traditions and food! It's not a surprise, I love food! And I would like to share with you some of the recipes I got from my friends.

Let's start with my friend Allan. He is a very nice guy from Texas, whom I was lucky to meet in Oslo. It was sad that he had to move back to the states, but I believe that I'll see him again. He shared with me his salsa recipe. I've been using it for the last half a year. Trust me, it's really good. Texicans know their tex-mex food. I haven't made any other salsa since. It's definitely a winner at our home. Though it is crazy spicy! If you are up for the challenge, here is the recipe:

